    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-01-13T09:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-01-13T09:45:00-05:00" n="340"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d340">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/5251: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Munro</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-01-13T09:00:00-05:45">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 13, 1928—9 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 12:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>23. Antonio Medrano, one of the substitute judges of the Supreme Court, has been
                    selected as the Liberal Vice Presidential candidate on the ticket with
                        Moncada.<note n="3" xml:id="d340fn3">Head of the Liberal Party.</note> His
                    friends have asked me to ascertain whether the Department sees any reason to
                    question the constitutionality of his election. Apparently article 126<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d340fn4">
                        <ref target="frus1912#pg_997">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1912, pp. 997</ref>, <ref
                            target="frus1912#pg_1008">1008</ref>.</note> is the only one which could
                    possibly bear on the question.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Munro</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
